Introduction

You have been asked by Danielle Sherman, CTO of Blackwell Electronics, to predict the customers brand preferences that are missing from the incomplete surveys by conducting two classification methods in R. Once you have determined which classifier C5.0or RandomForest works better on the provided data set, she would like you to predict the brand preferences for the incomplete survey responses and prepare a report of your findings.

This task requires you to prepare one deliverable for Danielle Sherman:

  • Customer Brand Preferences Report.A report in a Zip file that includes:

    • A brief summary in Word or Excel of your methods and results that includes:

      • The classifiers you tried.

      • The classifier you selected to make the predictions, including a rationale for selecting the method you did and the level of confidence in the predictions.

      • The predicted answers to the brand preference question for the instances of survey results that are missing that answer.

      • A chart that displays the customer preference for each brand based on the combination of the actual answers and the predicted answers to the brand preference survey question.

    • The results of each classifier you ran exported from R

Extracting and Cleaning Data

Before performing EDA on the dataset, I will first extract the data and clean it up, if necessary

completeResponses_Data <- read.csv(file = './SurveyData/CompleteResponses.csv')
basic_eda <- function(data)
{
  glimpse(data)
  df_status(data)
  freq(data) 
  profiling_num(data)
  plot_num(data)
  describe(data)
}

This is created to do some basic EDA on a dataset passed into it, as an argument.

I checked for any missing data in the dataset and it returned zero. This makes it easy to proceed to the next step.

names(completeResponses_Data)<-c("salary","age","education_level","car","zipcode","credit","computer_brand")

Changing the names of the headings of each data column to make it easier to manipulate the dataset with code.

completeResponses_Data$education_level<-factor(completeResponses_Data$education_level,labels=c("Lower than High School Degree","High School Degree","Some College","4-Year College DegreeI","Master's, Doctoral or Professional Degree"),ordered=TRUE)

From the plots above, it can be deduced that a higher percentage of customers buy the Sony brand. It can also be seen that customers with high and low salaries prefer to purchase Sony, while customers with mid-income ranges prefer to purchase Acer.

This can be explained thus: Customers with higher salaries can afford the Sony, while customers with low income prefer Sony because it lasts longer and maybe because it helps them identify with high-income earners. However, I will need more data to verfiy my assumptions.

Its also notable that across all ages, Sony is purchased more.

I created salary_bin, to see if I can deduce any specific preferences of computer brand based on salary scale. After plotting frequency of salary_bin histogram, I noticed my histogram is very simple to the salary histogram. Hence I discarded the salary_bin column as it appeared not to have much of an impact on my deductions.

My previous deductions still stands: High income earners have a strong preference for purchasing the Sony brand, followed by Low income earners.

# Distribution of education level 

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(zipcode))+ geom_bar(fill="slateblue4")+labs(title = "DISTRIBUTION OF ZIP CODES", x = "ZIP CODES", y = "COUNT")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold.italic", color = "blue",size = 6,angle = 90)) 

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(zipcode))+ geom_bar(aes(fill=computer_brand))+labs(title = "DISTRIBUTION OF ZIP CODES", x = "ZIP CODES", y = "COUNT")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold.italic", color = "blue",size = 6,angle = 90))

The graphs above aim to determine if zipcode is a strong determinant of the computer brand purchased. And the graphs prove that zipcode does not affect the brand purchased, as most customers from all the zipcodes have a strong preference for Sony.

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(car))+ geom_bar(fill="slateblue1")+labs(title = "DISTRIBUTION OF CAR TYPE", x = "PRIMARY CAR", y = "COUNT")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold.italic", color = "blue",size = 6,angle = 90)) 

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(car))+ geom_bar(aes(fill=computer_brand))+labs(title = "DISTRIBUTION OF CAR TYPE", x = "PRIMARY CAR", y = "COUNT")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold.italic", color = "blue",size = 6,angle = 90))

Does the car the customer drives, determine their taste in computer brands? The graphs above show that the computer brand purchased is not determined by the type of car the customer drives. Again across all car brands, sony is the highest purchased computer brand.

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(computer_brand))+ geom_bar(fill="slateblue2")+labs(title = "DISTRIBUTION OF COMPUTER BRAND", x = "COMPUTER BRAND", y = "COUNT")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold.italic", color = "blue",size = 6,angle = 90))

The graph above shows the number of Acer computers bought against the number of Sony computers bought. We can see clearly, that Sony computers are bought almost twice as much as Acer computers.

Deductions so far:

Salary earned determines the computer brand purchased. Zipcode, Education level and Car brand does not determine the computer brand purchased.

Next we do Multi-variable analysis.

EDA: Comparing multiple variables

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(x = computer_brand, y = salary, fill = computer_brand)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +

From the boxplot above, we can see that Sony has a higher average of purchases from high income customers, while Acer is on average, bought from a mostly middle-income earners. This further confirms our deductions from the previous section.

Plotting against credit does not show any significant differences. This leads to the deduction that the credit available to a customer does not determin the computer brand they will purchase.

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(age,credit))+
  geom_point(aes(color=computer_brand),size=0.5) + geom_smooth(aes(age,credit),method = lm)+labs(title = "COMPARING COMPUTER BRANDS AGAINST AGE AND CREDIT LIMIT", x = "age", y = "credit")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Just like the previous graph, the line of best fit in the ggplot above cut through a graph with no clear differentiation of the values being plotted. This lets us know that credit limit and age together are not able to give strong indicators for a preferred computer brand.

So moving forward, we will be using salary against age to compare with other variables, as these two together gave a more informative ggplot.

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(age, salary)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = computer_brand), size = 0.5) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(age, salary), method = lm) +
  labs(title = "COMPUTER BRANDS AGAINST SALARY, AGE", x = "age", y = "salary") +
  facet_wrap(~ zipcode) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "red"))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The above plot shows the salary against age graph across the different zipcodes. It is easy to note that there is no significant difference of the respective graphs. This confirms our previous deduction that zipcode does not significantly determine the computer brand purchased.

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

We repeat the same plot we did with Zipcodes, this time with the car brands that customers have. And we notice the same thing. All the graphs look similiar. ANd this confirms our deduction in the previous section, that the type of car the customer drives does not determine the computer brand they are likely to purchase.

ggplot(completeResponses_Data, aes(age, salary)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = computer_brand), size = 0.5) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(age, salary, group=computer_brand), method = lm) +
  labs(title = "COMPUTER BRANDS AGAINST SALARY, AGE", x = "age", y = "salary") +
  facet_wrap(~ education_level)+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "red"))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

And lastly, we repeat the process for education level. Again the graphs all look very similar. This further confirms our deduction that the customers education level does not determine the computer brand they are likely to purchase.

So far, from our EDA, we have found two values that determine the computer brand that a customer will buy. The two values are: Salary (the most powerful determiner) Age (Not as powerful as salary and is only significant when combined with the customers salary)

Next, we train our model.

Training the Model

set.seed(107)
isTrain <- createDataPartition(y = computer_brand,
                               p = .75,
                               list = FALSE)

trainingData <- completeResponses_Data[isTrain,]
testingData <- completeResponses_Data[-isTrain,]

#Deploying the Trained Model

Now that we have selected our model and fine-tuned it, we can deploy it on the surveyIncomplete dateset.

But preliminary steps first.

We need to extract the surveyIncomplete data and then clean it up, where necessary.

surveyIncomplete__data <- read.csv(file = './SurveyData/SurveyIncomplete.csv')
head(surveyIncomplete__data)

nrow(surveyIncomplete__data[duplicated(surveyIncomplete__data),])
## [1] 0
names(surveyIncomplete__data)<-c("salary","age","education_level","car","zipcode","credit","computer_brand")
surveyIncomplete__data$education_level<-factor(surveyIncomplete__data$education_level,labels=c("Lower than High School Degree","High School Degree","Some College","4-Year College DegreeI","Master's, Doctoral or Professional Degree"),ordered=TRUE)

surveyIncomplete__data$car<-factor(surveyIncomplete__data$car,labels=c("BMW","Buick"," Cadillac","Chevrolet","Chrysler","Dodge","Ford","Honda","Hyundai","Jeep","Kia","Lincoln","Mazda","Mercedes Benz","Mitsubishi", "Nissan","Ram","Subaru","Toyota","None of the above"),ordered=TRUE)

surveyIncomplete__data$zipcode<-factor(surveyIncomplete__data$zipcode,labels=c("New England","Mid-Atlantic","East North Central","West North Central","South Atlantic", "East South Central" , "West South Central","Mountain","Pacific"),ordered=TRUE)

surveyIncomplete__data$computer_brand<-factor(surveyIncomplete__data$computer_brand,labels=c("Acer","Sony"),ordered=TRUE)
predictBrands_gbmTrained <- predict(gbmFit_trainedt, newdata = surveyIncomplete__data)
# Replace the target variable in the data set
surveyIncomplete__data$computer_brand <- predictBrands_gbmTrained

In the code above, I replaced the target variable (computer_brands) with the predicted values from the fined-tuned gbm model.

Plotting an lm graph gives a very similiar output for both datasets.

Conclusions:

  1. Salary is the strongest determinant of the computer brand a customer will buy. This is seen when the feature importance is plotted for the different prediction models.

  2. Age, when combined with salary, is a good determinant of the computer brand a customer will buy. Age alone is not a strong enough determiner.

  3. All other features (zipcode, car, education level etc) did not show any significant prediction of the target variable(computer brand). Even when combined with age and salary, these other features did not show any significant changes.

  4. The gbm model performed remarkably well in predicting the target variable and this was shown when all EDA performed on the modified surveyIncomplete dataset gave a similiar graph to the EDA performed on the completeResponses dataset.
